Using unique_ptr correctly is memory safe. For example:<p><pre><code>  std::unique_ptr<int> p(new int(1));
  std::unique_ptr<int> q = p;
</code></pre>
Should fail.<p>You can strong arm it into break but you can also reuse a pointer locally in Go after it was sent over a channel.

To be fair, proper codepoint processing is a pain even in Java, which was created back when Unicode was in 16-bit mode. Now that it&#x27;s extended to 32-bits, proper Unicode string looping looks something like this:<p><pre><code>    for(int i = 0; i < string.length();) {
        final int codepoint = string.codePointAt(i);
        i += Character.charCount(codepoint);
    }</code></pre>
